# Cursor rules — soothsayer

Soothsayer is the analysis + serving + on-chain-publish layer of a
two-repo system. The sibling repo `scryer` (../scryer/) owns all
upstream data fetching.

Read `CLAUDE.md` for compact startup context, `AGENTS.md` for the same
rules in agent-tool format, and `reports/methodology_history.md` only
when methodology state matters.

## Hard rules

1. **No data fetching in soothsayer.** No `requests.get`, no
   `httpx`, no `yfinance.download`, no Helius / Jupiter / Kraken /
   Web3 RPC calls. Data lives at
   `/Users/adamnoonan/Library/Application Support/scryer/dataset/...`
   via `soothsayer.config.SCRYER_DATASET_ROOT`; the sibling
   `../scryer/dataset/...` checkout is offline-replay only.

2. **New data sources go in scryer first.** Add a methodology entry
   to `scryer/methodology_log.md`, implement the fetcher + schema in
   scryer, then consume the parquet here. Don't write one-off
   fetchers in soothsayer.

3. **Analysis reads scryer parquet.** Use `polars.read_parquet` or
   `pd.read_parquet` against `dataset/{venue}/{data_type}/v{N}/...`.

4. **Preserve `_schema_version`, `_fetched_at`, `_source` on read.**
   They are how reproducibility and schema-version-guard work.

5. **Soothsayer-side derived datasets use venue `soothsayer_v{N}`.**
   See the 2026-04-27 venue-versioning lock in
   `scryer/methodology_log.md`.

If a change would break any of these, stop and ask. The most common
trap: "let me just pull this quickly to test" — no. Use `scry import`
or `scry {venue} {data_type} ...` and read parquet.

## Read pattern (canonical)

```python
import polars as pl
from soothsayer.config import SCRYER_DATASET_ROOT

df = pl.read_parquet(
    SCRYER_DATASET_ROOT / "yahoo" / "equities_daily" / "v1" /
    "symbol=SPY" / "year=*.parquet"
)
assert df.select(pl.col("_schema_version").unique()).item() == "yahoo.v1"
```

Full guide: `docs/scryer_consumer_guide.md`. Keep startup docs compact:
current state, active gates, and links beat pasted historical rationale.
